05587nam a22007935i 9780812292848DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979578359  a97808122928487 a10.9783/97808122928482doi  a(DE-B1597)469620  a(OCoLC)948780149  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ792.U6 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a305.2223  aHT 16912rvk0(DE-625)rvk/53377:1 aCrain, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading Children :bLiteracy, Property, and the Dilemmas of Childhood in Nineteenth-Century America /cPatricia Crain. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b35 color, 45 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Children and Books -- tChapter 1. Literacy, Commodities, and Cultural Capital: The Case of Goody Two-Shoes -- tChapter 2. The Literary Property of Childhood: The Case of the ‘‘Babes in the Wood’’ -- tChapter 3. Colonizing Childhood, Placing Cherokee Children -- tChapter 4. ‘‘Selling a Boy’’: Race, Class, and the Literacy Economy of Childhood -- tChapter 5. Children in the Margins -- tChapter 6. Raising ‘‘Master James’’: The Medial Child and Phantasms of Reading -- tCoda. Bedtime Stories -- tAppendix. ‘‘The Children in the Wood’’ -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean for a child to be a "reader" and how did American culture come to place such a high value on this identity? Reading Children offers a history of the relationship between children and books in Anglo-American modernity, exploring long-lived but now forgotten early children's literature, discredited yet highly influential pedagogical practices, the property lessons inherent in children's book ownership, and the emergence of childhood itself as a literary property.The nursery and schoolroom version of the social contract, Crain argues, underwrote children's entry not only into reading and writing but also into a world of commodity and property relations. Increasingly positioned as an indispensable form of cultural capital by the end of the eighteenth century, literacy became both the means and the symbol of children's newly recognized self-possession and autonomy. At the same time, as children's legal and economic status was changing, "childhood" emerged as an object of nostalgia for adults. Literature for children enacted the terms of children's self-possession, often with explicit references to property, contracts, or inheritances, and yet also framed adult longing for an imagined past called "childhood."Dozens of colorful illustrations chart the ways in which early literature for children was transformed into spectacle through new image technologies and a burgeoning marketplace that capitalized on nostalgic fantasies of childhood conflated with bowdlerized fantasies of history. Reading Children offers new terms for thinking about the imbricated and mutually constitutive histories of literacy, property, and childhood in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries that ground current anxieties and long-held beliefs about childhood and reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChildrenxBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aLiteracyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocializationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z978311048